[[File:A Mosque in Mahe.jpg|thumb|A mosque in Mahe]]
{{Islam by country}}
'''Islam in the Indian Ocean''' was established by [[Muslim]] [[sea]] [[merchants]] well before the European discovery of [[Seychelles]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Exploring Islam|url=http://www.nation.sc/index.php?art=6953|publisher=www.nation.sc|accessdate=2 March 2013}}</ref> However, unlike in other island states including the [[Comoros]] and [[Maldives]], there were no permanent inhabitants in Seychelles until the French settlement in 1770. Today, the Muslim population of the islands is reported to be only 1.1%, roughly 900 people.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seychelles Population|url=http://www.historycentral.com/nationbynation/Seychelles/Population.html|publisher=www.historycentral.com|accessdate=2 March 2013}}</ref> Many of its island neighbors in the southern [[Indian Ocean]], including [[Comoros]], the [[Maldives]] and [[Zanzibar]], have a much larger Muslim influence because of their colonization by Muslims, before [[Europe]]an colonization. [[Mauritius]] also has a much higher Muslim population due to the importation of labour from [[British India]] on a scale not seen in Seychelles. The government of Seychelles allows 15 minutes of religious broadcasting every Friday for the Muslim community.

